Customizing MessageBoxes in .NET can be a bit tricky, but don't worry, I've got you covered.

First, let's talk about what you're trying to achieve. You want to show error and warning message boxes with a specific sound (Ding!) and a red colored cross mark. The default `MessageBox.Show()` method doesn't give us much flexibility in terms of customization.

However, we can use the `MessageBox` class's constructor overload that takes an icon parameter to specify the type of message box you want to display. For example:
```csharp
MessageBox.Show("Error message", "Title", MessageBoxButtons.OK, MessageBoxIcon.Error);
```
This will show a standard error message box with a red cross mark.

To add the Ding! sound, we can use the `System.Media` namespace and play a specific sound file when the message box is shown. You'll need to add a reference to this namespace in your project.
```csharp
using System.Media;

// ...

MessageBox.Show("Error message", "Title", MessageBoxButtons.OK, MessageBoxIcon.Error);
SoundPlayer player = new SoundPlayer(@"C:\path\to\ding.wav");
player.Play();
```
Note that you'll need to replace the path with the actual location of the sound file on your system.

One common approach is to create a custom MessageBox class that inherits from the standard `MessageBox` class and adds the customization features we want. Here's an example:
```csharp
public static class CustomMessageBox
{
    public static void ShowError(string message, string title)
    {
        SoundPlayer player = new SoundPlayer(@"C:\path\to\ding.wav");
        player.Play();
        MessageBox.Show(message, title, MessageBoxButtons.OK, MessageBoxIcon.Error);
    }

    public static void ShowWarning(string message, string title)
    {
        SoundPlayer player = new SoundPlayer(@"C:\path\to\ding.wav");
        player.Play();
        MessageBox.Show(message, title, MessageBoxButtons.OK, MessageBoxIcon.Warning);
    }
}
```
You can then use these custom methods to show error and warning message boxes with the desired sound and icon.

As for the red colored cross mark, that's already handled by the `MessageBoxIcon.Error` parameter in the constructor overload. If you want to customize the appearance of the message box further, you might need to look into using a third-party library or creating your own custom dialog box from scratch.

