So you're looking for a clear understanding of MVP, MVC, and MVVM. These patterns are all about separating concerns in your application's architecture, making it easier to maintain and scale.

Let's start with what issues these patterns address. The main problem they solve is the tight coupling between the presentation layer (the UI) and the business logic (the model). When you mix these two together, it becomes a nightmare to change or replace either one without affecting the other. These patterns help decouple them, making your code more modular and flexible.

Now, let's talk about what they have in common. All three patterns follow a similar structure: Model-View-Presenter/Controller/ViewModel. The model represents your domain objects, the view is responsible for rendering the UI, and the presenter/controller/viewmodel acts as an intermediary between them. This separation of concerns makes it easier to test, maintain, and extend your application.

The main difference lies in how they handle the interaction between the view and the presenter/controller/viewmodel. In MVP (Model-View-Presenter), the presenter is responsible for binding the model to the view. This means the view doesn't have a direct reference to the model; instead, it interacts with the presenter through an interface. This makes it easier to unit test because you can mock out the presenter and isolate the interaction between the view and the model.

In MVC (Model-View-Controller), the controller is responsible for updating the view directly when the model changes. This means the view has a direct reference to the model, which can make it harder to test and maintain.

MVVM (Model-View-ViewModel) is similar to MVC but replaces the controller with a viewmodel. The viewmodel acts as an intermediary between the view and the model, exposing data and command objects that the view needs. This makes it easier for the view to interact with the model without having a direct reference to it.

To illustrate this, let's consider a simple example in C#:
```csharp
// MVP Example
public class UserPresenter : IUserPresenter
{
    private readonly IUserView _view;
    private readonly IUserModel _model;

    public UserPresenter(IUserView view, IUserModel model)
    {
        _view = view;
        _model = model;
    }

    public void LoadUser()
    {
        var user = _model.GetUser();
        _view.BindUser(user);
    }
}

public class UserView : IUserView
{
    private readonly IUserPresenter _presenter;

    public UserView(IUserPresenter presenter)
    {
        _presenter = presenter;
    }

    public void BindUser(User user)
    {
        // Update the UI with the user data
    }
}
```

```csharp
// MVC Example
public class UserController : Controller
{
    private readonly IUserModel _model;

    public UserController(IUserModel model)
    {
        _model = model;
    }

    public void LoadUser()
    {
        var user = _model.GetUser();
        View.BindUser(user);
    }
}

public class UserView
{
    private readonly UserController _controller;

    public UserView(UserController controller)
    {
        _controller = controller;
    }

    public void BindUser(User user)
    {
        // Update the UI with the user data
    }
}
```

```csharp
// MVVM Example
public class UserViewModel : ViewModelBase
{
    private readonly IUserModel _model;

    public UserViewModel(IUserModel model)
    {
        _model = model;
    }

    public ObservableCollection<User> Users { get; set; }

    public void LoadUsers()
    {
        var users = _model.GetUsers();
        Users = new ObservableCollection<User>(users);
    }
}

public class UserView
{
    private readonly UserViewModel _viewModel;

    public UserView(UserViewModel viewModel)
    {
        _viewModel = viewModel;
    }

    public void BindUsers(ObservableCollection<User> users)
    {
        // Update the UI with the user data
    }
}
```
These examples illustrate how each pattern handles the interaction between the view and the presenter/controller/viewmodel. In MVP, the presenter is responsible for binding the model to the view through an interface. In MVC, the controller updates the view directly when the model changes. In MVVM, the viewmodel exposes data and command objects that the view needs.

One common approach is to use a framework or library that provides built-in support for these patterns, such as ASP.NET MVC for MVC or WPF for MVVM. This can simplify the implementation and make it easier to follow best practices.

I hope this helps clarify the differences between MVP, MVC, and MVVM!

Calculating someone's age in C# can be a bit tricky, but I've got you covered. 

The most straightforward way is to use the `DateTime` class and its methods. Here's an example:

```csharp
public static int CalculateAge(DateTime birthDate)
{
    var today = DateTime.Today;
    var age = today.Year - birthDate.Year;

    if (today.Month < birthDate.Month || (today.Month == birthDate.Month && today.Day < birthDate.Day))
        age--;

    return age;
}
```

This function takes a `DateTime` representing the person's birthday and returns their age in years. It first calculates the difference between the current year and the birth year, then subtracts one if the current month is before the birth month or if both months are equal but the current day is before the birth day.

However, this approach doesn't account for leap years, which can cause issues when dealing with February 29th. To handle this, you could use a more complex calculation:

```csharp
public static int CalculateAge(DateTime birthDate)
{
    var today = DateTime.Today;
    var age = today.Year - birthDate.Year;

    if (today.Month < birthDate.Month || (today.Month == birthDate.Month && today.Day < birthDate.Day))
        age--;

    // Handle leap years
    if ((birthDate.Month == 2 && birthDate.Day == 29) ||
        (today.Month == 2 && today.Day == 29))
    {
        var isLeapYear = IsLeapYear(today.Year);
        if (!isLeapYear)
            age--;
    }

    return age;
}

public static bool IsLeapYear(int year)
{
    return year % 4 == 0 && (year % 100 != 0 || year % 400 == 0);
}
```

This version of the function checks whether a given year is a leap year and adjusts the age accordingly.

One common approach to calculating age in years, months, and days is to use the `DateTime` class's methods for adding and subtracting time intervals. Here's an example:

```csharp
public static (int Years, int Months, int Days) CalculateAge(DateTime birthDate)
{
    var today = DateTime.Today;
    var age = new TimeSpan(today.Year - birthDate.Year, today.Month - birthDate.Month, today.Day - birthDate.Day);

    return (
        age.Days / 365,
        (age.Days % 365) / 30,
        age.Days % 30
    );
}
```

This function returns a tuple containing the person's age in years, months, and days. Note that this approach assumes a non-leap year has 365 days and a leap year has 366 days.

As for edge cases like February 29th, you can use the `DateTime` class's methods to handle these situations correctly:

```csharp
public static (int Years, int Months, int Days) CalculateAge(DateTime birthDate)
{
    var today = DateTime.Today;
    var age = new TimeSpan(today.Year - birthDate.Year, today.Month - birthDate.Month, today.Day - birthDate.Day);

    // Handle February 29th
    if ((birthDate.Month == 2 && birthDate.Day == 29) ||
        (today.Month == 2 && today.Day == 29))
    {
        var isLeapYear = IsLeapYear(today.Year);
        if (!isLeapYear)
            age = new TimeSpan(age.Days - 1, 0, 0);
    }

    return (
        age.Days / 365,
        (age.Days % 365) / 30,
        age.Days % 30
    );
}
```

This version of the function adjusts the age accordingly when dealing with February 29th.

