I totally understand your pain! You're right, a 400 status code is not always an error. In fact, it's often a perfectly valid response from the server with information about what went wrong.

The issue here is that `HttpWebRequest.GetResponse()` throws an exception when the status code is not in the range of 200-299 (which are considered successful). To handle this, you can catch the `WebException` and then check the status code of the response. If it's a 400, you can read the error stream to get more information about what went wrong.

Here's an example:
```csharp
try
{
    HttpWebRequest request = (HttpWebRequest)WebRequest.Create("http://example.com");
    // ...
    HttpWebResponse response = (HttpWebResponse)request.GetResponse();
}
catch (WebException ex)
{
    if (ex.Status == WebExceptionStatus.ProtocolError)
    {
        HttpWebResponse errorResponse = (HttpWebResponse)ex.Response;
        if (errorResponse.StatusCode == HttpStatusCode.BadRequest)
        {
            using (Stream stream = errorResponse.GetResponseStream())
            {
                // Read the error message from the response stream
                StreamReader reader = new StreamReader(stream);
                string errorMessage = reader.ReadToEnd();
                Console.WriteLine(errorMessage);
            }
        }
    }
}
```
Alternatively, you can create a separate method that handles getting the response even if it's not successful. This way, you can encapsulate this logic and avoid repeating yourself:
```csharp
private HttpWebResponse GetResponse(HttpWebRequest request)
{
    try
    {
        return (HttpWebResponse)request.GetResponse();
    }
    catch (WebException ex)
    {
        // ...
    }
}

// Usage:
HttpWebRequest request = (HttpWebRequest)WebRequest.Create("http://example.com");
// ...
HttpWebResponse response = GetResponse(request);
```
One common approach is to set `HttpWebRequest.DefaultMaximumErrorResponseLength` to a larger value if you expect large error responses. This will ensure that you get the entire response stream even if it's large.

