So you're looking for a way to call a method after a delay in Android, similar to how you would do it in Objective C. 

One common approach is to use the `Handler` class, which allows you to schedule a task to be executed at a later time. Here's an example of how you can use it:
```java
new Handler().postDelayed(new Runnable() {
    @Override
    public void run() {
        // Call your method here
        myMethod();
    }
}, 5000); // delay for 5 seconds
```
This will call the `myMethod()` after a 5-second delay.

Alternatively, you can use the `Timer` class as suggested in the context. Here's an example:
```java
Timer timer = new Timer();
timer.schedule(new TimerTask() {
    @Override
    public void run() {
        // Call your method here
        myMethod();
    }
}, 5000); // delay for 5 seconds
```
Both of these approaches will allow you to call a method after a specified delay without blocking the UI thread.

One thing to note is that if you're calling this from the main thread (i.e., the UI thread), you may want to use `runOnUiThread()` or `postDelayed()` on a `Handler` associated with the main thread, to ensure that your code runs on the correct thread. 

Also, keep in mind that using `Timer` can be less efficient than using `Handler`, especially if you're dealing with complex tasks or multiple delays. But for simple cases like this one, it should work just fine.

