The LD_PRELOAD trick! It's a clever way to override functions from shared libraries, like libc.so. Essentially, it allows you to load your own custom library before the standard ones, so that your functions get called instead of theirs.

Let me give you an example. Suppose we want to implement our own `malloc` and `free` functions. We can create a shared object (a .so file) with these implementations:
```c
// my_malloc.so
#include <stdlib.h>

void* malloc(size_t size) {
    // Our custom implementation of malloc
    printf("My malloc called for %zu bytes\n", size);
    return malloc(size); // Call the original malloc function
}

void free(void* ptr) {
    // Our custom implementation of free
    printf("My free called for pointer %p\n", ptr);
    free(ptr); // Call the original free function
}
```
Then, we can set `LD_PRELOAD` to point to our shared object:
```bash
$ LD_PRELOAD=/path/to/my_malloc.so ls
```
Now, when we run `ls`, it will use our custom `malloc` and `free` functions instead of the standard ones. This is because our library gets loaded before libc.so.

One common approach is to use this trick for testing or debugging purposes. For example, you could create a library that logs every memory allocation or deallocation, which can be super helpful when tracking down memory-related issues in your code.

Keep in mind that `LD_PRELOAD` only works with shared libraries (those ending in .so). If you're working with static libraries, this trick won't help.

