So you want to read a text file named `test.txt` and print its content to the console. I'd recommend using `fgets()` instead of `fscanf()`. Here's why:

`fscanf()` can be tricky when it comes to reading strings, because it doesn't leave any whitespace characters in the buffer. This means that if you're trying to read a string with multiple words, `fscanf()` will only store the first word and discard the rest.

On the other hand, `fgets()` reads an entire line into the buffer, including any whitespace characters. It's also safer because it doesn't risk overflowing your buffer like `fscanf()` can.

Here's some sample code to get you started:
```c
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    FILE *file = fopen("test.txt", "r");
    if (file == NULL) {
        perror("Error opening file");
        return 1;
    }

    char buffer[999]; // You can adjust this size as needed

    while (fgets(buffer, sizeof(buffer), file)) {
        printf("%s", buffer);
    }

    fclose(file);
    return 0;
}
```
This code opens the `test.txt` file in read mode (`"r"`), and then uses a loop to read each line into the `buffer`. The `fgets()` function returns `NULL` when it reaches the end of the file, so we can use that as our loop condition.

Note that I'm using `sizeof(buffer)` as the second argument to `fgets()`, which tells it how many bytes to read at most. This is a good practice to avoid overflowing your buffer.

One common approach if you need to process the file line by line (e.g., splitting strings at whitespace) would be to use `strtok()` on each line after reading it with `fgets()`. But for simple printing, this should do the trick!

