I think I see what's going on here. You're experiencing an OutOfMemory error when loading images into your ListView, specifically with the SimpleCursorAdapter. This is a common issue when dealing with large images.

First, let's talk about why this is happening. The problem lies in how you're loading the images. When you use `setImageURI` on an ImageView, it tries to load the entire image into memory at once. If the image is too large, this can cause an OutOfMemory error.

To fix this, we need to resize the images before loading them into the ListView. We can do this using a technique called "in-sample sizing." This involves calculating the best size for the image based on its original dimensions and the screen resolution.

Here's some sample code that demonstrates how to use in-sample sizing:
```java
public class ImageLoader {
    public static Bitmap decodeSampledBitmapFromUri(Context context, Uri uri, int reqWidth, int reqHeight) throws IOException {
        final int[] imageSize = getImageSize(uri);
        if (imageSize == null) return null;

        // Calculate the best in-sample size based on the original dimensions and screen resolution
        int inSampleSize = calculateInSampleSize(imageSize[0], imageSize[1], reqWidth, reqHeight);

        // Decode the image with the calculated in-sample size
        BitmapFactory.Options options = new BitmapFactory.Options();
        options.inSampleSize = inSampleSize;
        return BitmapFactory.decodeStream(context.getContentResolver().openInputStream(uri), null, options);
    }

    private static int[] getImageSize(Uri uri) throws IOException {
        InputStream is = context.getContentResolver().openInputStream(uri);
        BitmapFactory.Options options = new BitmapFactory.Options();
        options.inJustDecodeBounds = true;
        BitmapFactory.decodeStream(is, null, options);
        return new int[]{options.outWidth, options.outHeight};
    }

    private static int calculateInSampleSize(int width, int height, int reqWidth, int reqHeight) {
        int inSampleSize = 1;
        if (width > reqWidth || height > reqHeight) {
            final int halfWidth = width / 2;
            final int halfHeight = height / 2;
            while ((halfWidth / inSampleSize) >= reqWidth && (halfHeight / inSampleSize) >= reqHeight) {
                inSampleSize *= 2;
            }
        }
        return inSampleSize;
    }
}
```
You can then use this `ImageLoader` class to load the images into your ListView:
