Capturing the active window's screenshot is a great feature for your screen capturing application. To do this, you'll want to get the handle of the foreground window using `GetForegroundWindow` from the Windows API.

Here's an example of how you can use P/Invoke to achieve this:
```csharp
using System.Runtime.InteropServices;

[DllImport("user32.dll")]
static extern IntPtr GetForegroundWindow();

// ...

IntPtr hWnd = GetForegroundWindow();
```
Once you have the handle, you'll need to get its position and size on the screen. You can do this using `GetWindowRect` from the Windows API:
```csharp
[DllImport("user32.dll")]
static extern bool GetWindowRect(IntPtr hWnd, out RECT lpRect);

[StructLayout(LayoutKind.Sequential)]
public struct RECT
{
    public int left;
    public int top;
    public int right;
    public int bottom;
}

// ...

RECT rect;
GetWindowRect(hWnd, out rect);
```
Now that you have the position and size of the active window, you can use `Graphics.CopyFromScreen` to capture its screenshot:
```csharp
using (Bitmap bitmap = new Bitmap(rect.right - rect.left, rect.bottom - rect.top))
{
    using (Graphics g = Graphics.FromImage(bitmap))
    {
        g.CopyFromScreen(rect.left, rect.top, 0, 0, bitmap.Size);
    }
}
```
This will give you a `Bitmap` object representing the screenshot of the active window.

One thing to note is that this approach assumes there's only one "main window" in the application. If your application has multiple windows and you want to capture all of them, you'll need to modify the code accordingly.

Also, keep in mind that this is just a basic example, and you may want to add error handling and other features depending on your specific requirements.

