I'm glad you're still using singletons for factory classes, but I understand why you might be confused about their reputation. The thing is, singletons aren't inherently bad; it's how people misuse them that causes problems.

Let me break it down. Singletons are useful when you need to ensure only one instance of a class exists throughout the application. This can be beneficial for things like logging or configuration management. However, when used as a "glorified global," singletons become problematic.

The issue is that they often grow into unmanageable classes with helper methods for every little use case. This makes them difficult to test and maintain. As Alex Miller puts it in his article "Patterns I hate #1: Singleton" (2007), singletons are a problem when people don't have a solid grasp of object-oriented concepts.

One common approach is to use dependency injection instead of singletons. This way, you can decouple your classes from the singleton instance and make them more modular and testable.

Here's an example of how you might refactor a singleton into a dependency-injected class:
```java
// Singleton version
public class Logger {
    private static Logger instance;

    public static Logger getInstance() {
        if (instance == null) {
            instance = new Logger();
        }
        return instance;
    }

    // ...
}

// Dependency-injected version
public interface ILogger {
    void log(String message);
}

public class Logger implements ILogger {
    @Override
    public void log(String message) {
        // logging logic here
    }
}
```
In the dependency-injected version, you can inject an instance of `ILogger` into your classes instead of relying on a singleton. This makes it easier to test and maintain your code.

So, while singletons aren't inherently bad, their misuse can lead to problems. It's essential to use them judiciously and consider alternative approaches like dependency injection when designing your applications.

