So you're trying to make a thread wait until it's notified, but you're getting an `IllegalMonitorStateException` when calling `Thread.wait()`. This is because `wait()` can only be called by the owner of the object's monitor. 

In other words, if you're not synchronized on the object before calling `wait()`, you'll get this exception.

Here's a simple example to illustrate this:
```java
public class MyThread extends Thread {
    public void run() {
        try {
            // This will throw an IllegalMonitorStateException because we're not synchronized on obj
            obj.wait();
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            System.out.println("Interrupted");
        }
    }

    private Object obj = new Object();

    public static void main(String[] args) throws InterruptedException {
        MyThread thread = new MyThread();
        thread.start();
        // Now, let's synchronize on obj and call notify() to wake up the thread
        synchronized (obj) {
            obj.notify();
        }
    }
}
```
In this example, `MyThread` is trying to wait on `obj`, but it's not synchronized on `obj` when calling `wait()`. This will throw an `IllegalMonitorStateException`.

To fix this, you need to synchronize on the object before calling `wait()` or `notify()`. Here's how you can modify the code:
```java
public class MyThread extends Thread {
    public void run() {
        try {
            synchronized (obj) { // Synchronize on obj here
                obj.wait();
            }
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            System.out.println("Interrupted");
        }
    }

    private Object obj = new Object();

    public static void main(String[] args) throws InterruptedException {
        MyThread thread = new MyThread();
        thread.start();
        // Now, let's synchronize on obj and call notify() to wake up the thread
        synchronized (obj) {
            obj.notify();
        }
    }
}
```
By synchronizing on `obj` before calling `wait()`, we ensure that the current thread owns the object's monitor, and `wait()` will work as expected.

One common approach is to use a `Lock` object instead of synchronizing directly on an instance variable. This can be more flexible and easier to manage in complex scenarios:
```java
import java.util.concurrent.locks.Lock;
import java.util.concurrent.locks.ReentrantLock;

public class MyThread extends Thread {
    private final Lock lock = new ReentrantLock();

    public void run() {
        try {
            lock.lock(); // Acquire the lock
            obj.wait();
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            System.out.println("Interrupted");
        } finally {
            lock.unlock(); // Release the lock
        }
    }

    private Object obj = new Object();

    public static void main(String[] args) throws InterruptedException {
        MyThread thread = new MyThread();
        thread.start();
        // Now, let's synchronize on obj and call notify() to wake up the thread
        synchronized (obj) {
            obj.notify();
        }
    }
}
```
This way, you can easily manage locks and avoid deadlocks in your multithreaded program.

