Validating XML files against XSD files can be a bit of a pain, but don't worry, I've got you covered.

First off, if you're generating XML files programmatically, it's a good idea to validate the content while you're writing it, rather than first writing it and then reading it back for validation. This way, you can catch any errors right away and avoid having to re-write the entire file.

In Java, you can use the JDK API for XML validation with SAX-based writers. Here's an example of how you might do this:
```java
import javax.xml.XMLConstants;
import javax.xml.transform.Source;
import javax.xml.transform.stream.StreamSource;
import javax.xml.validation.Schema;
import javax.xml.validation.SchemaFactory;
import javax.xml.validation.Validator;

// Create a schema factory and get the schema for your XSD file
SchemaFactory sf = SchemaFactory.newInstance(XMLConstants.W3C_XML_SCHEMA_NS_URI);
Schema schema = sf.newSchema(new File("path/to/your/xsd/file.xsd"));

// Create a validator from the schema
Validator validator = schema.newValidator();

// Create a source from your XML file (e.g. using a SAX parser)
Source source = new StreamSource(new File("path/to/your/xml/file.xml"));

// Validate the XML against the XSD
validator.validate(source);
```
Alternatively, if you're using Stax for writing content, you can use the `Validator` class to validate your XML as you write it.

If you don't want to roll your own validation code, there are some great libraries out there that can help. One popular option is XMLBeans, which has built-in support for schema validation and can convert Java objects to an XML document and vice versa. Another option is JAXB (Java Architecture for XML Binding), which also provides a way to validate XML against XSD.

As for command-line tools, I've heard good things about LiquidXML Studio 2008 (v6) - it's got a user-friendly interface and can handle validation, although the free version has some limitations. If you're looking for something more lightweight, you might want to try XMLFox, but be warned that it can be a bit confusing at first!

One common approach is to use an IDE like Eclipse or IntelliJ IDEA, which often have built-in support for XML and XSD validation. This way, you can get instant feedback on your code as you write it.

