So you're wondering why we should default to using `vector` over `list` in STL? Well, it's because `vector` is generally a more efficient choice for most use cases. 

Let me give you an example. Suppose you have a large dataset that you need to store and frequently access elements by their index. In this case, `vector` would be a better choice because it provides constant-time random access (i.e., accessing an element at a specific index takes the same amount of time regardless of its position in the vector). 

Here's some sample code to illustrate this:
```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>

int main() {
    std::vector<int> vec;
    for (int i = 0; i < 1000000; ++i) {
        vec.push_back(i);
    }

    // Accessing an element at a specific index
    int idx = 500000;
    std::cout << "Element at index " << idx << ": " << vec[idx] << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```
In this example, accessing the element at index `idx` takes constant time because `vector` provides random access.

Now, if you need to frequently insert or remove elements from the middle of your dataset, a `list` might be a better choice. This is because `list` provides O(1) insertion and removal operations when inserting or removing elements at arbitrary positions in the list (using iterators). 

Here's some sample code to illustrate this:
```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <list>

int main() {
    std::list<int> lst;
    for (int i = 0; i < 1000000; ++i) {
        lst.push_back(i);
    }

    // Inserting an element at a specific position in the list
    int idx = 500000;
    lst.insert(lst.begin() + idx, 99999);

    return 0;
}
```
In this example, inserting an element at index `idx` takes constant time because `list` provides O(1) insertion operations when using iterators.

So, to summarize: if you need to frequently access elements by their index or perform random access, use a `vector`. If you need to frequently insert or remove elements from the middle of your dataset, consider using a `list`.

One common approach is to use a `vector` as the underlying storage for your data and then use an iterator or pointer to access the elements. This way, you can take advantage of the efficiency of `vector` while still being able to insert or remove elements at arbitrary positions in the list.

