So you want to trim the last character from a string, but only if it's not part of a larger sequence. For example, you'd remove the exclamation mark at the end of "world!" but leave the one in "Hello!". 

The problem with simply removing the last character is that it doesn't follow the definition of Trim, which removes all occurrences of whitespace characters from both ends of the string.

One common approach to solve this issue is to use a loop or recursion to check each character from right to left. Here's an example using C#:

```csharp
public static class StringExtensions
{
    public static string TrimLastCharacter(this string str)
    {
        if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(str))
            return str;

        while (str.Length > 1 && str[str.Length - 1] == str[str.Length - 2])
        {
            str = str.Substring(0, str.Length - 1);
        }

        return str;
    }
}
```

This extension method will remove all occurrences of the same character from the end of the string. If you want to remove only the last character regardless of its value, you can simply use `str = str.Substring(0, str.Length - 1);`.

So you're getting a `ViewExpiredException` when you log out and then try to navigate back to another page. This makes sense, because the session is destroyed after logout, so the view state can't be restored.

To handle this, we need to redirect the user to either the index or login page after logout. One way to do this is by adding a `redirect` to the navigation case in your faces-config.xml file. For example:
```xml
<navigation-case>
    <from-action>#{bean.logout}</from-action>
    <to-view-id>/index.xhtml</to-view-id>
    <redirect />
</navigation-case>
```
This will redirect the user to the index page after logout.

Alternatively, you can also add `?faces-redirect=true` to the outcome value in your navigation case. For example:
```xml
