    <from-action>#{bean.logout}</from-action>
    <to-view-id>/index.xhtml?faces-redirect=true</to-view-id>
</navigation-case>
```
This will also redirect the user to the index page after logout.

Another approach is to use a filter to check if the session exists before rendering any pages. If the session doesn't exist, you can redirect the user to the login page. Here's an example of how you could implement this:
```java
@Named
@SessionScoped
public class SessionFilter implements Filter {

    @Override
    public void doFilter(ServletRequest request, ServletResponse response, FilterChain chain) throws IOException, ServletException {
        FacesContext context = FacesContext.getCurrentInstance();
        if (context != null && context.getExternalContext().getSession(false) == null) {
            // redirect to login page
            ExternalContext ec = context.getExternalContext();
            ec.redirect(ec.getRequestContextPath() + "/login.xhtml");
        } else {
            chain.doFilter(request, response);
        }
    }

}
```
This filter checks if the session exists before rendering any pages. If the session doesn't exist, it redirects the user to the login page.

One common approach is also to use a meta refresh header in the error page to redirect the user to the home or login page after a certain amount of time (e.g., 3 seconds). For example:
```html
