So you're trying to access non-static variables from a static method, but it's not working. That makes sense because, as the explanation on Stack Overflow says, static methods don't belong to any particular instance of the class - they belong to the class itself.

Think about it like this: when you call `MyClass.myMethod()`, the method doesn't know which specific instance of `MyClass` you're referring to. It's just a generic method that belongs to the class as a whole, not an individual instance.

So, if you try to access non-static variables (which are tied to instances) from within a static method, it won't work because the method doesn't know which instance to use.

The solution is either to make your fields static, so they belong to the class and can be accessed by both static and non-static methods. Or, you could make your methods non-static, so they're tied to an instance of the class and can access its non-static variables.

Here's a simple example:
```java
public class MyClass {
    private int myNonStaticField;

    public void myNonStaticMethod() {
        System.out.println(myNonStaticField);
    }

    public static void myStaticMethod() {
        // This won't work because myNonStaticField is not static
        // System.out.println(myNonStaticField);

        // But this will work if we make it static
        MyClass.staticMyNonStaticField = 10;
        System.out.println(MyClass.staticMyNonStaticField);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        myStaticMethod();
    }
}
```
In this example, `myNonStaticField` is a non-static field that can only be accessed by non-static methods. But if we make it static, like `staticMyNonStaticField`, then it can be accessed from both static and non-static methods.

One common approach to avoid this issue altogether is to use instance variables (non-static) whenever possible, and reserve static variables for things that truly belong to the class as a whole, like constants or utility functions. But if you need to access instance variables from a static method, making them static is one way to go!

Returning multiple values from a function in C++ can be done in several ways, but I'd recommend using `std::pair` for two return values. It's a simple and efficient way to do it.

For example:
```cpp
std::pair<int, int> divide(int dividend, int divisor) {
    int quotient = dividend / divisor;
    int remainder = dividend % divisor;
    return std::make_pair(quotient, remainder);
}
```
If you need more than two return values, `boost::tuple` (or in C++11 and newer, `std::tuple`) is a great option. It's similar to `std::pair`, but can hold multiple values.

```cpp
std::tuple<int, int, double> calculate(int x, int y) {
    int sum = x + y;
    double average = (x + y) / 2.0;
    return std::make_tuple(sum, average, x * y);
}
```
One thing to keep in mind is that `std::pair` and `std::tuple` are value types, so they're passed by value by default. If you have large objects or a lot of data, it might be more efficient to return a pointer to the result instead.

```cpp
struct Result {
    int sum;
    double average;
    int product;
};

Result* calculate(int x, int y) {
    // ...
}
```
Alternatively, if your function is doing some complex calculation and you want to make it easier to use, consider returning an object that contains all the results. This can be a `struct` or even a full-fledged class.

```cpp
struct CalculatorResult {
    int sum;
    double average;
    int product;
};

CalculatorResult calculate(int x, int y) {
    // ...
}
```
It's worth noting that in C++17 and later, you can use structured binding to make working with `std::tuple` even easier.

```cpp
auto [sum, average, product] = calculate(x, y);
```
Overall, the choice of how to return multiple values from a function depends on the specific requirements of your code. But in general, using `std::pair`, `boost::tuple`, or returning an object with all the results is a good way to go!

