So you're wondering about StackOverflowError? It's actually a pretty common issue, especially when it comes to recursion. Essentially, a StackOverflowError occurs when your function calls nest too deeply.

Let me give you an example of what I mean by "nesting too deeply". Suppose we have a simple recursive function like this:
```java
public void foo() {
    foo();
}
```
If we call `foo()` once, it will just keep calling itself indefinitely. And when the space used to keep track of what functions you're in is filled up (i.e., the stack overflows), you'll get a StackOverflowError.

The context mentions that excessively deep or infinite recursion is usually the culprit behind these errors. So if you're experiencing this issue, it's worth taking a closer look at your recursive functions and see if there's a way to optimize them or avoid the infinite loop altogether.

One common approach is to add some kind of base case to your recursive function, so that it knows when to stop calling itself. For example:
```java
public void foo(int depth) {
    if (depth > 10) return; // Add a base case!
    System.out.println("Hello!");
    foo(depth + 1);
}
```
In this example, we've added a `depth` parameter that keeps track of how many times the function has called itself. If it reaches a certain threshold (in this case, 10), we return without calling ourselves again.

Of course, there are other ways to deal with StackOverflowError, but this should give you an idea of where to start!

